<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-prisms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Prisms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li>Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
            <li>Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>
        The <term>surface area</term> of a solid is the total area of all its outer faces.
        It tells us how much material is needed to cover or construct a solid object.
    </p>
    <p>
        In this section, we begin with cubes and cuboids, then extend the idea to other prisms.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-surface-area-of-cubes-and-cuboids">
        <title>Surface Area of Cubes and Cuboids</title>
        <activity>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <term>Materials Needed:</term>
                    <ol marker="a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Solids cube, or cuboid wood waste blocks
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Grid/graph paper or plain paper
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Rulers
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Pre-made nets of cubes or cuboids (optional)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
                    <p>
                        <term>Instructions:</term>
                        <ol marker="i)">
                            <li>
                                <p>Choose one solid object (cube or cuboid).</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Create a net for the chosen object (either by unfolding a model or using drawn net templates).</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Trace the faces onto grid paper or measure them using a ruler or string.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Calculate the area of each face.</p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>Add up all face areas.</p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image label="borders-squares-identical">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Missing line
                            \draw (0,4) -- (4,4);
                            
                            
                            \fill[gray!30] (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                            
                            % Drawing the edges
                            \draw (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                            \draw (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);
                            
                            % Adding dimension labels
                            \node[left] at (0,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[left] at (0,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[above] at (2,8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (2,-8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (6,0) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (-2,0) {8 cm};
                            
                            % Adding rectangle labels
                            \node at (2,6) {A};
                            \node at (2,2) {B};
                            \node at (2,-2) {C};
                            \node at (2,-6) {D};
                            \node at (-2,-2) {E};
                            \node at (6,-2) {F};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>
                    What will happen if the surface area doubles in size?
                </p>
                <p>
                    Why do bigger cubes have more surface area?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>

        <insight>
            <p>
                A <term>cube</term> has <m>6</m> identical square faces.
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Cube} = 6s^2
                </me>
                where <m>s</m> = side length of the cube.
            </p>

            <p>
                A <term>cuboid</term> (rectangular prism) has 6 rectangular faces.
                <me>
                    \text{Surface Area of a Cuboid} = 2(lw + lh + wh)
                </me>
            </p>

            <p>
                where <m>l</m> = length, <m>w</m> = width, <m>h</m> = height.
            </p>
            <p>
                A <m>\textbf{prism}</m> is a geometric object with two identical, parallel bases and straight sides connecting them.
            </p>
            <p>
                The surface area of a cube or cuboid is the total area of all its faces. It can be calculated by finding the area of each face and then adding them together.
            </p>
            <p>
                A <m>\textbf{cuboid}</m> is also called a rectangular Prism. A <m> \textbf{cube}</m> is a rectangular prism with all sides of equal length.
            </p>
            <p>
                Examples of right prisms are  cylinders, rectangular prisms, cubes and triangular prisms.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\textbf{Types of Prisms}</m> include rectangular and cube prisms, Triangular Prisms and Cylinders.
            </p>
        </insight>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out the surface area of a cube whose side is <m>12 \ \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The area of one face of the cube is:
                    <me>
                        S.A = 6s^2
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 6(12^2)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 6(144)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 864 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   Find the surface area of the following rectangular prism:
                </p>   
                   <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image label="rectangular-prism-one" >
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Set background color
                            \fill[cyan!50] (-1, -0.5) rectangle (8, 3.5);

                            % Draw the front face
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5,2) -- (0,2) -- cycle;

                            % Draw the top face
                            \draw[thick] (0,2) -- (2,3) -- (7,3) -- (5,2);
                            \draw[dashed] (2,3) -- (2,1);

                            % Draw the side face
                            \draw[thick] (5,0) -- (7,1) -- (7,3);
                            \draw[dashed] (2,1) -- (7,1);
                            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,1);
                            % Dimension labels
                            \node[below] at (2.5,0) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (7,0.8) {14 cm};
                            \node[left] at (0,1) {3 cm};
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                   </image> 
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                     Sketch and label the net of the prism.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="rectangular-prism-two">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[rotate=90]
                        % Set background color
                        \fill[cyan!50] (-5, -2) rectangle (8, 12.5);

                        % Draw main rectangle
                        \draw[thick] (-5,0) rectangle (8,10);

                        % Vertical overlapping rectangle
                        \draw[thick] (2,-2) --(2,10);
                        \draw[thick] (-3,0) --(-3,-2) --(2,-2) --(2,0);
                        % Vertical division lines
                        \draw[thick] (-3,10) -- (-3,0);
                        \draw[thick] (4,10) -- (4,0);
                        \draw[thick] (-3,10) --(-3,12) --(2,12) --(2,10);

                        % Dimension labels
                        \node[above] at (3,10) {\huge 2 cm};
                        \node[above] at (0,12) {\huge  8 cm};
                        \node[above] at (5,10) { \huge  8 cm};
                        \node[right] at (7,5) {\huge  14 cm};
                        \node[above] at (-4, 10) {\huge  2 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                     Find the areas of the different shapes in the ne
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{large rectangle} = \amp \text{ perimeter of small rectangle} \times \text{length} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp (3+8+3+8)\text{cm} \times 14\text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 22\text{cm}  \times 14\text{cm}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 308\text{cm}^2  </mrow>
                    </md>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 2 \, \text{small rectangle} \amp = 2(8 \text{cm} \times 3\text{cm} ) </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 2(18) \,\text{cm}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 36\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                     Find the sum of the areas of the faces
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                    <mrow>\text{large rectangle}  + \text{small rectangle} = \amp (308 + 36)\text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 344 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md> 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The surface area of the rectangular prism is <m>344 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Work out the surface area of the cube whose side is <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
            <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image label="borders-surface-area-cube">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Drawing the vertical part of the net with different colors
                            \fill[yellow!10] (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) --(4,4)   -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                            \fill[blue!20](0,4) --(4,4) --(4,8) --(0,8) --cycle;
                            % Missing line
                            \draw (0,4) -- (4,4);

                            % Drawing the horizontal part of the net with different colors
                            \fill[blue!20] (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);

                            \fill[blue!20] (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- cycle;
                            \fill[cyan!20] (-4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (-4,0) -- cycle;
                            \fill[cyan!20] (4,-4) -- (8,-4) -- (8,0) -- (4,0) -- cycle;

                            % Drawing the edges
                            \draw (0,-8) -- (0,-4) -- (0,0) -- (0,4) -- (0,8) -- (4,8) -- (4,4) -- (4,0) -- (4,-4) -- (4,-8) -- (0,-8) -- cycle;
                            \draw (-4,0) -- (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (8,0) -- (8,-4) -- (4,-4) -- (0,-4) -- (-4,-4) -- (-4,0);

                            % Adding dimension labels
                            \node[left] at (0,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,6) {8 cm};
                            \node[right] at (4,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[left] at (0,2) {8 cm};
                            \node[above] at (2,8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (2,-8) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (6,0) {8 cm};
                            \node[below] at (-2,0) {8 cm};

                            % Adding rectangle labels
                            \node at (2,6) {A};
                            \node at (2,2) {B};
                            \node at (2,-2) {C};
                            \node at (2,-6) {D};
                            \node at (-2,-2) {E};
                            \node at (6,-2) {F};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                    </image>

                <p>
                    The surface area of the cube is:
                </p>
                <p>
                    The area of one face.
                <md>
                    
                    <mrow> = \amp 8 \,\text{cm} \times 8 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 64 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
                    There are 6 faces therefore the surface area of the cube is;
                <md>    
                    <mrow> = \amp  6 \, \times 64 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 384 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md> 
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_vmvoo6nc">
                    The surface area of the cube is 384 <m>\text{cm}^2</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the surface area of a rectangular prism measuring <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m> by <m>3 \, \text{cm}</m> by <m>14 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The surface area of the rectangular prism is calculated as:
                    <me>
                        S.A = 2(lw + lh + wh)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2((8 \times 3) + (8 \times 14) + (3 \times 14))
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2(24 + 112 + 42)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 2(178)
                    </me>
                    <me>
                        = 356 \text{ cm}^2
                    </me>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

